04514nam a22006375i 9781400882892DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20162017nju    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)984653378  a97814008828927 a10.1515/97814008828922doi  a(DE-B1597)479620  a(OCoLC)956520789  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aHIS0100002bisacsh1 aTher, Philipp, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEurope since 1989 :bA History /cPhilipp Ther. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2016] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (440 p.) :b13 halftones. 21 line illus. 3 maps.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface to the English Edition -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Where the East Meets the West: Crisis and Reform Debates in the 1980s -- t3. The Revolutions of 1989-91 -- t4. Getting on the Neoliberal Bandwagon -- t5. Second-Wave Neoliberalism -- t6. Capital Cities Compared -- t7. The Great Recession: 2008-9 and Its Consequences -- t8. Southern Europe: The New East? -- t9. Cotransformation: The Case of Germany -- t10. The Roads Not Taken -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe year 1989 brought the fall of the Berlin Wall and the collapse of communism in Eastern Europe. It was also the year that the economic theories of Reagan, Thatcher, and the Chicago School achieved global dominance. And it was these neoliberal ideas that largely determined the course of the political, economic, and social changes that transformed Europe-both east and west-over the next quarter century. This award-winning book provides the first comprehensive history of post-1989 Europe.Philipp Ther-a firsthand witness to many of the transformations, from Czechoslovakia during the Velvet Revolution to postcommunist Poland and Ukraine-offers a sweeping narrative filled with vivid details and memorable stories. He describes how liberalization, deregulation, and privatization had catastrophic effects on former Soviet Bloc countries. He refutes the idea that this economic "shock therapy" was the basis of later growth, arguing that human capital and the "transformation from below" determined economic success or failure. Most important, he shows how the capitalist West's effort to reshape Eastern Europe in its own likeness ended up reshaping Western Europe as well, in part by accelerating the pace and scope of neoliberal reforms in the West, particularly in reunified Germany. Finally, bringing the story up to the present, Ther compares events in Eastern and Southern Europe leading up to and following the 2008-9 global financial crisis.A compelling and often-surprising account of how the new order of the New Europe was wrought from the chaotic aftermath of the Cold War, this is essential reading for understanding Europe today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh1 aHughes-Kreutzmüller, Charlotte.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311063859240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400882892zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400882892423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400882892.jpg  a978-3-11-063859-2  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK